<script language=javascript> <!-- //Disable right click script - By www.BBeginner.com // var message="Function Disabled"; //////////////// function clickIE() {if (document.all) {(message);return false;}} function clickNS(e) {if (document.layers(document.getElementById&&!document.all)) { if (e.which==2e.which==3) {(message);return false;}}} if (document.layers) {document.captureEvents(Event.MOUSEDOWN);document.onmousedown=clickNS;} else{document.onmouseup=clickNS;document.oncontextmenu=clickIE;} document.oncontextmenu=new Function("return false") // --> </script>

@Lyrafiel 1. Go to Google Sheets and open a new Google Sheet document using your Google account. 2. In the toolbar for the new Google Sheet, go to Tools -> Script editor 3. Create script for: Script as Web App 4. A code editor will open. Replace any sample code in the editor with the code I gave. 5. Within the inserted code, replace the value of foldername with the name of folder for which you want a listing. 6. Save the code; application will ask for a file name. 7. Run by clicking on the right-pointing triangle in the button bar. 8. ‘Authorization required ‘ pop up will appear; grant authorization. 9. Go back to your Google Drive and refresh. You will see an excel file there.
The resulting file should contain something like this.
Given that the naming convention you use for the files are as follows: For cleans: <name><space>CL.png 1-6 CL.png For typeset: <name><space>TS.png 1-6 TS.png

Frostbane 19-Nov-20 09:33 AM

Frostbane 19-Nov-20 05:43 PM
Now that I think about it, it all makes sense. When using chroma subsampling, the chroma image is smaller, and needs to be upscaled when decoding. If the decoder uses a bilinear to upscale, the chroma will bleed to adjacent pixels. Some browsers may use a more crude decoding, with nearest upscaling, which won't bleed. All of this happen at the decoding stage with a perfectly fine file. I am enlightened.

Nightmare888888 17-Jun-21 10:39 PM
Hey everyone, after taking a break to focus on IRL things (which still applies, I'm not going to be very active), I'm back and working on a program that could theoretically do an automated cleaning process using machine learning. It's still in the very early access stages, but I have a completed alpha (with a very inaccurate detection model) that I am going to improve over the coming months. The biggest priority for me is to improve the quality and accuracy of text detection for the program. What this means is that I'm going to need a LOT of panels and that also means that I'm going to be going through hundreds, possibly thousands of photos and manually marking them for where text is. This is probably unsustainable, and although necessary, means that there's less focus on coding in quality of life changes and other functionalities. In that regard, if anyone has a lot of time, and would be willing to help, please let me know. The improvements to the model also means that I'm going to need a lot of raws, but the machine learning model uses 640x640 images, meaning that it'll automatically resize images to fit that size, no matter what their actual sizes are (which leads to horrible warping and less accurate detection). This means that I would really appreciate any non-stitched pages that you might have available, but if not I have a very very rough program for cutting them down to size. I'm really excited to continue to work on this project and hopefully make something that is usable, but it's going to take a while. The proof of concept is completed, but I don't think there will be any significant progress for the next month or so.

/* <javascriptresource> <name>Show layer</name> <category>scripts_rd</category> <enableinfo>true</enableinfo> <menu>automate</menu> </javascriptresource> */ function layerMap(set, func) { var n = set.layerSets.length; for (var i = 0; i < n; i++) layerMap(set.layerSets[i], func); var n = set.artLayers.length; for (var i = 0; i < n; i++) func(set.artLayers[i]) func(set); } function findLayersByName(set, name) { res = new Array(); layerMap(set, function(layer) { if (layer.name == name) res.push(layer); }); return res; } var doc = app.activeDocument; var layerName = "RD"; var rd_layers = findLayersByName(doc, layerName); if (rd_layers.length == 0) alert("Can't find " + layerName + " layer."); else { var show = true; // true show, false hide for(var i = 0; i < rd_layers.length; i++) rd_layers[i].visible = show; }

Nightmare888888 09-Oct-21 01:10 AM
Hey, just wanted to clarify for staff so that we get a much cleaner perspective on the bato.to thing: 1. Is the base website, bato.to itself dangerous? Technically no, the issue that has become clear is that bato.to is redirecting to suspicious and straight up malicious ads, which can be very dangerous. These ads are also running suspicious scripts in the background. Any time that you're redirected away from the batoto page to one of these ad websites, you get put at risk. (You can also refer to my basic intro to XSS - cross-site scripting - pinned in general) 2. Is this a malicious act by bato.to to intentionally harm users? Even though it may not be, they are complacent in allowing their website to redirect users to other ads and websites that are malicious and can intentionally harm batoto's own users. 3. How do I know if I've been affected? You can run a free scan on your computer using malwarebytes, but if you're on your phone there isn't much to do, and just because the way that phone operating systems work, you should be alright. Apple heavily restricts downloads for iPhones, so even though they are not impregnable (cough pegasus cough) they are pretty safe (edited)
3
Nutzlos 09-Oct-21 02:55 AM
guess I might also post this here before it gets lost in #general
uBlock Origin rule to prevent the bato.to popups. However, I think this only works in Firefox because Chrome sucks (see https://github.com/gorhill/uBlock/wiki/Inline-script-tag-filtering#caveats for more info).
bato.to##^script:has-text(oackoubs)
Might be possible to get a similar effect in chrome by disabling all inline scripts but that might break the site and I haven't tested it yet.
Nutzlos 09-Oct-21 03:45 AM
uBlock Origin rule for chrome
||bato.to^$inline-script @@||bato.to/chapter^$inline-script
Both have a possibility to break in the future: The Firefox filter will break if the ad domain (oackoubs dot something) changes or is obfuscated further, but should be easy enough to update. The chrome one being less specific would not prevent popups if they started adding those to the chapter reader (which they're not currently doing). Also, it may or may not break some features of the site but for now it seems to be good enough to read chapters without popups.
